MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, I am Hector and I will be your instructor, and today is RE-ENTRY day!
In this Lesson I will teach you how to perform the Deorbit-Reentry-Landing procedure for the Gemini Spacecraft.

Atmospheric entry or re-entry is the movement of an object from outer space into and through the gases of an atmosphere surrounding some planets. This procedure allows a controlled atmospheric entry, descent, and landing of spacecraft on Earth.
Atmospheric Drag and Aerodynamic Heating can cause an atmospheric breakup capable of completely disintegrating any spacecraft. That's why it is so important to master this procedure.
Just before re-entry, the Gemini capsule will jettison the Retrograde section, leaving only the cone-shaped spacecraft holding the crew.

The tip/nose of the Gemini capsule contains a parachute system. Small explosives will deploy the parachutes to slow the capsule's descent. Shortly after, the capsule will make a big splash in the ocean and float until a rescue ship retrieves the vehicle and astronauts.
Let's get started. We are currently about 80 minutes from the start of the re-entry.

The first thing we will do in this lesson is to take a look at the Deorbit-Reentry-Landing procedure. You might notice the use of C/Bs in the procedures. These refer to the circuit breaker switches. On Gemini these look like normal switches, and are located on the left/right and overhead panels.

We need to maneuver the Gemini spacecraft to Retrograde attitude. Hit 'V' on your keyboard to open [V]IEW SELECTOR, then select [CENTER PEDESTAL]. In the [PROP MOTOR VALVES] section set [OAMS] to [OPEN].
Now, in [CNTL PWR] section set [OAMS] to [ON].
The [OAMS] is needed to maneuver to the Retro Burn attitude.
Make sure that [ATTITUDE CONTROL] is set to [PLAT] in the [CENTER PEDESTAL].
This will hold the spacecraft Attitude to the PLATFORM selected.
Then, set [PLATFORM] to [BEF] on the [CENTER PEDESTAL].
Now the spacecraft should be changing its attitude to retrograde. Look at the [FDAI] ball.
Set the Computer Mode to PRE LN, then press START on the computer. Press ROGER when the computer is running the PRE LN program.

Now, let's check how much time we have left to the Retro Burn. Once again hit 'V' on your keyboard to open [V]IEW SELECTOR if it's not already open, then select [PILOT'S PANEL]. Press [1] on the MDIU.
Next press [9] on the MDIU.
And finally press [READ OUT].
The new reading will show time until Retro burn in minutes:seconds, where the message is formatted as MMM:SS. We have about one orbit to prepare for entry, much more than what was really needed.
One important tool during entry is the Event Timer, so let's start by learning how to use it. Set the Event Timer mode to STOP, then open [C] MISSION TOOLS -> COCKPIT FUNCTIONS -> RESET EVENT TIMER.
We will set the Event Timer to count down from [30:00] minutes (in DOWN (DN) mode). Turn the Event Timer Dial counterclockwise (Left) to increase numbers until the display shows [30:00] minutes.

Once [30] is Displayed in the minutes digits, turn Dial clockwise back to middle position [0]. You can use the other positions to increase/decrease seconds and minutes if needed. Next, turn [LEFT PIN] DOWN to [STOP].
Turn [RIGHT PIN] down to [DN].
Then set it to start by pushing the Event Timer [LEFT PIN] up to [STBY].
We will run the Pre-Retro checklist when this clock reaches zero.
Let's get familiar with the entry procedures while waiting. Open the checklists from the MISSION PAD and find the ENTRY section, and the LANDING section.
These sections contain all the checklists we will be using today. Read through them and try to get a good overview of the procedures. It will be time well invested.

You can also switch the flight mode to a manual mode such as PULSE, RATE COMMAND, or DIRECT, and align the space craft in roll. Try to manually align the craft now so roll is zero, and that you have the Earth below you (heads up). Press ROGER when complete.
Timescale until the Event Timer reaches 00:00, STOP the Event Timer, and then press ROGER.
The first part of the ENTRY section is the PRE RETRO checklist. This checklist will basically prepare us for retro.
It is important that you correctly set up the event timer when instructed to, as the OBC/CORE 19 might be unavailable while the OBC loads. RUN the checklist now.

You will need to monitor Core 19 (press READ OUT multiple times). As you proceed with the checklist, one of the last steps will be to start the Event Timer when CORE 19 reaches 02000 (020:00 minutes), before loading the OBC entry module. Loading takes 10 minutes, which will leave us about 10 minutes of time before the burn.

We should now be about 10 minutes away from the planned ignition. If you are not yet familiar with the steps ahead, spend the next couple of minutes getting familiar with the 256 and 1min to retro checklists. It will be hectic.
The next checklist we will run is 256 SEC TO RETRO (4 minutes, 16 seconds). We will use the RUN feature to do this. Do this now.

The first thing it asks you to do is to wait for the Event Timer to reach T -4:16 min, 256 seconds before the burn. This checklist will verify critical switch configurations. Proceed when at T -4:16min.
At the end of this checklist, it will ask you to perform the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist. This will be where all the sequencer buttons will be pressed. A lot will happen in a short time, so be prepared.
During the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist, you need to pay close attention to Sequencers [CENTER PANEL]. Each sequencer light will illuminate yellow. [IND RETRO ATT] will be the first.

As each sequencer is pressed and completes, it will turn green. Anyways, back to the checklist. Complete the 256 SEC TO RETRO checklist and hit the check mark when it asks you to START 1 MIN TO RETRO at the end of the checklist.
Then RUN the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist.
Maintain requested attitude while waiting for the Event Timer to reach T -1min and then complete the checklist following the steps and timing precisely.
After pressing the [JETT RETRO] sequencer button, you are ready to run the [POST RETRO JETTISON] checklist. Do this now.
Make sure [COMPUTER] is set to [RE ENT] mode and press START to turn it on [bright Green light].
Now your pilot's skills will be proven!
Change the Gemini Spacecraft Attitude manually, so those needles point to the center. Do this by changing the ROLL, PITCH and YAW attitudes. These are measured in degrees.
Remember the following (default) keyboard keys: [W: PITCH DOWN], [S: PITCH UP], [A: YAW LEFT], [D: YAW RIGHT], [Q: ROLL LEFT], [E: ROLL RIGHT].
Let's talk about maneuvering in the atmosphere. You need to be careful to not build up too much G-force. Do not exceed 10 G's.
Keep those needles centered as much you can in the upper parts of the atmosphere. Once drag is sufficient, air density will automatically move the spacecraft into a stable atmospheric trim attitude.
At this time, the only axis you need to control is ROLL. The capsule is designed to generate lift. When your heads are pointing down towards Earth, the lift vector points up.
When your heads are pointing up, the lift vector points down towards Earth.
When you reach 400 thousand feet altitude, roll the spacecraft to heads down, so the lift vector points up.
When 0.05G is detected, the IVIs will show the range to the touchdown point and will start to count down.

At this time roll so the spacecraft is in a heads up position, diving down into the atmosphere. Pay attention to the G-forces, and reverse the roll so the lift vector points up when it exceeds 3-4 G's.
The longer you keep the lift vector up, the longer the capsule will travel before splashing down. [optional: Try to maneuver so you get close to the splashdown point]
During reentry, your spacecraft will shake as it strikes the atmosphere, and you will see a bright yellow light wrapping around the capsule. Maneuver to maintain G-forces (below 10 G's) and range.
Once everything is calm again, it means you have performed the reentry successfully.
RUN the Landing checklist and follow it during the descent.
Now go to [V]IEW SELECTOR, then hit [COMMANDER'S PANEL]. Next take a look at the [40K] and [10.6K] indicators.
When the [40K] indicator lights up on the [COMMANDER'S PANEL], go to [V]IEW SELECTOR, hit [CENTER PEDESTAL], then press [HI ALT DROGUE]. This will deploy the Altitude Drogue.
Then, when the [10.6K] indicator lights up on the [COMMANDER'S PANEL], go to [V]IEW SELECTOR, hit [CENTER PEDESTAL] and press [PARA]. This will deploy the main Parachute.
The Landing attitude can be set after main chute deploy.
Watch the ALTITUDE GAUGE. When it displays 500 feet from ground, once again go to [V]IEW SELECTOR, hit [CENTER PEDESTAL], then press [LDG ATT] if you still have not done this.
Prepare for splashdown.
Congratulations, you just landed safely!
The final checklist to run is the POST LANDING checklist. RUN this now.
This will release the chute and power down things not needed after splashdown.
Congratulations, this completes the deorbit, entry and landing lesson. It has been a long lesson but an important one. Feel free to re-run if things are unclear.

Title: Tutorial 8 - Deorbit, Entry & Landing
Description: In this lesson we will learn how to perform the Deorbit-Reentry-Landing procedure which is a requirement for every Gemini Program mission.
BriefingText: On early Gemini flights, astronauts manually controlled much of the spacecraft's maneuvers during re-entry. Just before re-entry, the Gemini capsule would jettison the retrograde section, leaving only the cone-shaped spacecraft holding the crew. In most cases, the astronauts used the capsule's controls to maneuver it so that the large, blunt end faced the Earth. The friction generated from the spacecraft moving through the atmosphere at tremendous speeds produced intense heat. Without the heat shield on the base of the Gemini spacecraft, the astronauts inside the capsule wouldn't have been able to survive. Finally the Gemini Spacecraft lands safely in the Atlantic Ocean.
